\begin_layout Abstract
In recent years,
 bio-inspired optimization algorithms have been widely used for solving complex optimization problems.
 In this paper,
 we propose the Parallel Enzyme Action Optimization (PEAO) algorithm,
 a parallel bio-inspired optimization algorithm with a multi-strategy communication mechanism.
 The algorithm divides the population into multiple subpopulations that evolve in parallel,
 enhancing the exploration capability of the search space.
 PEAO combines adaptive search factors,
 local search procedures and communication mechanisms between subpopulations,
 reducing the probability of premature convergence and improving the quality of the obtained solutions.
 In addition,
 clustering techniques and a stopping criterion based on successive improvements of the best objective function value are incorporated to improve efficiency and reduce unnecessary objective function evaluations by terminating the search once convergence has been detected.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Keywords
Parallel optimization;
 Evolutionary techniques;
 Stochastic methods;
 high-dimensional problems;
 Multi-strategy communication
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The
\series bold
 
\series default
basic goal of global optimization is to find the global minimum of a continuous multidimensional function,
 which is defined as:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x^{*}=\mbox{arg}\min_{x\in S}f(x)\label{eq:eq1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

:
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S=\left[a_{1},b_{1}\right]\times\left[a_{2},b_{2}\right]\times\ldots\left[a_{n},b_{n}\right]
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset

 representing lower and upper bounds for each variable 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The continuous increase in the dimensionality and complexity of modern optimization problems has created a growing demand for optimization algorithms capable of efficiently exploring large and multimodal search spaces 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "DE_Large,Large1,Large2,Large3"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 while maintaining reasonable computational requirements.
 Such challenges often arise in mechanical design 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "mechanical design,mechanical design-1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 machine learning 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "machine_learning_1,machine_learning_2"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and data analysis 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "big data analysis"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 where the search landscape often contains many local optima.
 Although population-based metaheuristic algorithms have demonstrated significant success in addressing these problems,
 their performance often deteriorates as the dimensionality of the problem increases,
 leading to slow convergence,
 premature stagnation and excessive computational cost.
 Recent surveys have highlighted the continuous development of bio-inspired and evolutionary optimization algorithms,
 emphasizing the importance of balancing exploration,
 exploitation,
 scalability and computational efficiency in modern optimization problems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Osaba,Jian"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Moreover,
 recent adaptive evolutionary algorithms have demonstrated remarkable performance on large-scale optimization benchmarks,
 motivating the development of more efficient cooperative optimization frameworks 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Stanovov,Vakhnin"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The Enzyme Action Optimizer (EAO) is a recently introduced bio-inspired optimization algorithm that models the catalytic behavior of enzymes during biochemical reactions.
 Since its introduction by Rodan et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "EAO-1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 EAO has demonstrated competitive performance across a wide range of benchmark and real-world optimization problems.
 Recent studies have successfully applied EAO to infinite impulse response filter identification problems,
 where it exhibited strong convergence characteristics under different filter configurations 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "EAO-1-1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Furthermore,
 modified variants of EAO have been employed for the design of fractional-order PID controllers in nonlinear continuous stirred tank reactor systems,
 demonstrating effective control performance and robustness in challenging dynamic environments 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "EAO2."
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Enhanced EAO frameworks have also been proposed for feature selection in medical data classification tasks,
 achieving improved predictive performance through more effective exploration and diversity preservation mechanisms 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "EAO3"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 In addition to these applications,
 EAO has been successfully utilized for the design of robust two-degree-of-freedom PIDA controllers in magnetic levitation systems,
 highlighting its effectiveness in complex control engineering problems 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "EAO5"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 The algorithm has also been applied to parameter identification in nonlinear systems,
 further demonstrating its capability to handle challenging estimation and modeling tasks 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "EAO4-1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Moreover,
 recent research has introduced the Dynamic Enzyme Action Optimizer (DEAO),
 an adaptive variant of EAO that incorporates dynamic search mechanisms to improve the balance between exploration and exploitation and enhance optimization performance on classical benchmark functions 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "EAO4"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Collectively,
 these studies demonstrate the flexibility,
 robustness and adaptability of the EAO search mechanism across a diverse range of optimization applications.
 Despite these promising developments,
 the original EAO and most of its existing variants primarily rely on single-population search processes.

\series bold
 
\series default
Consequently,

\series bold
 
\series default
they may encounter difficulties when addressing large-scale and highly multimodal optimization problems where maintaining population diversity,
 preserving exploration capability and avoiding premature convergence become increasingly challenging.
 In addition,
 the absence of structured cooperation among search agents may limit the efficient dissemination of useful search information throughout the population.
 Motivated by these limitations,
 this work proposes a novel cooperative parallel framework termed Parallel Enzyme Action Optimizer (PEAO),
 which extends the original EAO through distributed population evolution and structured information exchange mechanisms.
 Although cooperative island-based evolutionary algorithms and distributed population models have been extensively investigated in the literature,
 the proposed PEAO should not be interpreted as a straightforward island implementation of the original EAO.
 Conventional island-model approaches typically rely on relatively independent subpopulations that periodically exchange individuals through predefined migration policies.
 In contrast,
 PEAO extends the original EAO by integrating adaptive propagation,
 multiple communication strategies,
 optional local search refinement and a convergence-based stopping mechanism within a unified cooperative optimization framework.
 Consequently,
 the proposed method combines several complementary mechanisms that jointly improve information dissemination,
 preserve population diversity and enhance the balance between exploration and exploitation,
 rather than simply parallelizing the original algorithm.
 Instead of evolving a single population,
 the search process is decomposed into several semi-independent subpopulations that perform exploration simultaneously while periodically exchanging information through dedicated communication mechanisms.
 A key component of the proposed framework is the introduction of an adaptive propagation mechanism that enables the controlled dissemination of high-quality solutions among clusters.
 By facilitating the transfer of promising search information across different regions of the population,
 the propagation process accelerates convergence while preserving sufficient diversity to maintain exploration capabilities.
 Although a recent study introduced a parallel EAO-based optimizer with a multi-strategy communication mechanism for breast cancer diagnosis 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "PEAO"
literal "false"

\end_inset

,
 its primary objective was hyperparameter optimization for a specific machine learning application.
 In contrast,
 the proposed framework is developed as a general-purpose continuous optimization algorithm and further extends the EAO framework through the integration of cooperative cluster evolution,
 adaptive propagation,
 optional local search,
 a convergence-based stopping mechanism and a systematic investigation of communication strategies.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The main contributions of this work can be summarized as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A cooperative parallel extension of the Enzyme Action Optimizer is proposed,
 based on the partitioning of the population into multiple interacting clusters that perform concurrent search operations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A propagation mechanism is introduced to facilitate the exchange of high-quality solutions among clusters,
 accelerating convergence while maintaining population diversity.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Multiple communication strategies are incorporated,
 enabling diverse forms of information exchange and cooperative interaction among subpopulations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A convergence-based stopping criterion that monitors successive improvements of the best objective function value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A scalable optimization framework is developed that improves the balance between exploration and exploitation and is particularly suitable for high-dimensional and computationally demanding optimization problems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike conventional island-model metaheuristics,
 which primarily rely on relatively independent subpopulations and predefined migration policies,
 the proposed PEAO integrates adaptive propagation,
 multiple communication strategies,
 convergence-based stopping and optional local refinement into a unified cooperative optimization framework.
 Furthermore,
 unlike previous parallel EAO variants developed for specific application domains,
 the proposed method is designed as a general-purpose optimizer for continuous black-box optimization problems.
 Consequently,
 the proposed framework extends the original EAO through the integration of multiple complementary search mechanisms rather than by simply parallelizing the original algorithm.
 The proposed PEAO is intended for continuous,
 single-objective,
 bound-constrained optimization problems,
 particularly black-box problems for which analytical gradient information is unavailable to the global search mechanism.
 Therefore,
 PEAO should be regarded as an extension of the original EAO rather than a direct parallel implementation,
 since it combines multiple complementary algorithmic mechanisms that fundamentally modify both the search dynamics and the cooperation among individuals.
 The method primarily targets nonlinear,
 multimodal and high-dimensional problems in which maintaining an effective balance between exploration and exploitation is essential.
 The core population-based search process remains gradient-free,
 while the optional BFGS procedure is employed only as a local refinement mechanism when applicable.
\end_layout

