\begin_layout Subsection

\series bold
PEAO Algorithm
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The proposed Parallel Enzyme Action Optimizer (PEAO) is a population-based metaheuristic designed for continuous,
 single-objective,
 bound-constrained optimization problems.
 Its global population-based search mechanism does not require analytical derivative information and is therefore applicable to continuous black-box optimization problems.
 PEAO aims to maintain an effective balance between global exploration and local exploitation while enhancing population diversity through parallel cooperative search.
 In PEAO,
 the population is divided into multiple semi-independent subpopulations that evolve concurrently within the 
\begin_inset Formula $D-$
\end_inset

dimensional search space and periodically cooperate through the proposed communication and propagation mechanisms.
 Each individual 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 represents a candidate solution to the optimization problem.
 Initially,
 a population of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 individuals is randomly generated within the prescribed search bounds and distributed among the available subpopulations.
 The objective function is evaluated for each individual and the best solution identified so far is denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{best}}.$
\end_inset

 The structure of PEAO was selected so that each algorithmic component addresses a distinct requirement of complex continuous optimization problems.
 The decomposition of the population into multiple subpopulations promotes population diversity and enables the simultaneous exploration of different regions of the search space.
 The sinusoidal operator introduces nonlinear perturbations around promising solutions,
 whereas the Lévy-flight and population-difference operators generate long-range and population-guided search movements.
 The greedy selection mechanism preserves improvements,
 the optional local search procedure refines promising solutions and the convergence-based stopping mechanism limits unnecessary objective function evaluations.
 Therefore,
 PEAO combines complementary mechanisms intended to address exploration,
 exploitation,
 diversity preservation,
 local refinement and computational efficiency rather than relying on a single update operator.
 During the optimization process,
 an adaptive factor 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is dynamically adjusted according to 
\begin_inset Formula $A=\sqrt{\frac{\mathrm{iter}}{T}},$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathrm{iter}\in{0,\ldots,T}$
\end_inset

 denotes the current iteration and 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is the maximum number of iterations.
 The adaptive factor increases monotonically from 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 and directly controls the contribution of the attraction term toward the current best solution in the candidate-generation equations.
 Compared with a linear schedule,
 the square-root formulation increases more rapidly during the early and intermediate stages of the optimization process and more gradually near its final stage.
 Consequently,
 guidance from the best solution is incorporated relatively early,
 while the sinusoidal,
 Lévy-flight and population-difference components continue to provide stochastic exploration.
 The selected schedule therefore combines progressive best-solution guidance with persistent stochastic perturbations throughout the search process.
 For each individual,
 three candidate solutions are generated using complementary search mechanisms.
 The first candidate is generated through a sinusoidal perturbation strategy guided by the current best solution.
 This operator introduces nonlinear oscillatory movements around promising regions of the search space and increases the diversity of the generated candidates.
 The sinusoidal component allows the direction and magnitude of the perturbation to vary during the optimization process,
 thereby reducing the probability that all individuals follow identical search trajectories.
 The second and third candidate-generation mechanisms combine Lévy-flight perturbations,
 population-difference information and attraction toward the current best solution.
 Two randomly selected individuals are first used to construct a difference vector,
 which introduces information about the spatial distribution of the current population.
 The Lévy-flight component additionally provides stochastic movements with occasional long steps,
 enabling the algorithm to investigate regions located away from the current population.
 Although the two candidates,
 denoted by 
\begin_inset Formula $C2A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $C2B$
\end_inset

,
 employ the same general sources of search information,
 they were designed to generate complementary search patterns.
 In 
\begin_inset Formula $C2A$
\end_inset

,
 both the Lévy perturbation and the scaling factor are vectors.
 Consequently,
 each decision variable may receive a different perturbation coefficient,
 resulting in dimension-specific and anisotropic search movements.
 This mechanism increases the diversity of the generated solutions and supports the investigation of different directions within the search space.
 In contrast,
 
\begin_inset Formula $C2B$
\end_inset

 employs a scalar Lévy coefficient and a scalar scaling factor.
 The same scalar coefficient is therefore applied across all decision variables,
 producing more coordinated movements along the population-difference and best-solution attraction directions.
 The coexistence of vector-based and scalar-based mechanisms provides complementary dimension-wise and coordinated search behaviors.
 Their combined use increases the variety of candidate solutions generated during each iteration and reduces dependence on a single search pattern.
 After the three candidate solutions have been generated,
 their objective function values are evaluated and the best candidate is selected.
 A greedy selection mechanism is subsequently applied.
 For a minimization problem,
 the current solution is replaced only when the selected candidate has an objective function value equal to or lower than that of the current solution.
 Consequently,
 accepted updates do not deteriorate the fitness of the corresponding individual.
 To further enhance local refinement,
 a local search procedure may be activated with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{l}=0.05$
\end_inset

.
 When triggered,
 the BFGS algorithm is applied to a promising current solution as an optional refinement stage.
 Since this procedure is invoked with a low probability,
 it does not constitute the primary search component of PEAO.
 The population-based candidate-generation process remains derivative-free,
 whereas BFGS is employed only when the objective function is sufficiently smooth and gradient information can be supplied or numerically approximated.
 For non-differentiable problems,
 the local-search stage can be disabled by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{l}=0$
\end_inset

 or replaced by an appropriate derivative-free local optimizer.
 Therefore,
 the global search mechanism of PEAO remains applicable to continuous black-box optimization,
 while the optional BFGS stage provides additional local refinement when appropriate.
 The BFGS local search is executed using the default stopping criteria of the optimization library implementation.
 Since local refinement is activated with a probability of only 5%,
 it does not dominate the computational cost of the proposed method.
 Furthermore,
 all objective function evaluations performed during the local search phase are included in the reported total number of objective function evaluations.
 At the end of each iteration,
 the global best solution is updated using the objective function values of the newly evaluated solutions.
 The convergence-based stopping criterion is then applied by monitoring the absolute change in the best objective function value between two consecutive iterations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\delta^{(\mathrm{iter})}=\left|f^{(\mathrm{iter})}_{\mathrm{min}}f^{(\mathrm{iter}-1)}_{\mathrm{min}}\right|.$
\end_inset

 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta^{(\mathrm{iter})}$
\end_inset

 remains below a predefined tolerance 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{t}$
\end_inset

 consecutive iterations,
 the optimization process is considered to have converged and is terminated.
 In this context,
 the term Similarity refers to the similarity of the optimization progress observed in successive iterations rather than to similarity among individuals,
 clusters or subpopulations.
 This stopping mechanism reduces unnecessary objective function evaluations when no meaningful improvement is detected.
 By combining sinusoidal perturbation,
 Lévy-flight movements,
 population-difference learning,
 adaptive best-solution guidance,
 greedy selection,
 optional local refinement and convergence-based termination,
 PEAO provides multiple complementary search behaviors within a unified optimization framework.
 These mechanisms are intended to maintain population diversity,
 reduce premature convergence,
 refine promising solutions and limit unnecessary objective function evaluations when solving complex continuous optimization problems.
 
\end_layout

