\begin_layout Subsection
Propagation Mechanism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The propagation mechanism enables information exchange among subpopulations by transferring high-quality solutions during the optimization process.
 Specifically,
 the best individual of a subpopulation is propagated to other subpopulations,
 replacing their worst-performing individual.
 This process enhances cooperation and accelerates convergence toward promising regions of the search space.
 To maintain low communication overhead and scalability,
 the proposed framework adopts simplified propagation strategies instead of conventional migration topologies.
 Four propagation methods are considered:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
One-to-One (1to1):
 A randomly selected subpopulation sends its best solution to another randomly selected subpopulation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
One-to-All (1toN):
 A randomly selected subpopulation propagates its best solution to all other subpopulations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
All-to-One (Nto1):
 The best solutions of all subpopulations are propagated to a single randomly selected subpopulation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
All-to-All (NtoN):
 Each subpopulation exchanges its best solution with all other subpopulations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These strategies promote the dissemination of high-quality solutions while preserving the computational efficiency of the parallel framework.
\end_layout

