\begin_layout Subsection
Communication Strategies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Optimal Replacement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
During communication,
 the best individuals from all cooperating subpopulations are propagated to each subpopulation,
 where they replace the worst individual.
 This strategy enables the rapid dissemination of high-quality search information while preserving the remaining individuals,
 thereby accelerating convergence and improving the overall search efficiency.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Optimal Mean Replacement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
During communication,
 a new candidate solution is constructed as the arithmetic mean of the best individuals from all cooperating subpopulations.
 The generated solution is subsequently used to replace the worst individual within each destination subpopulation.
 By integrating information from multiple high-quality solutions,
 this strategy facilitates smoother knowledge sharing,
 improves population diversity and promotes a more balanced trade-off between exploration and exploitation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Circular Optimal Replacement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The subpopulations are organized in a logical ring topology.
 During each communication phase,
 the best individual from the preceding subpopulation is transferred to the subsequent subpopulation,
 where it replaces the worst individual.
 Consequently,
 high-quality search information is propagated progressively throughout the population,
 promoting balanced cooperation among subpopulations while preserving diversity.
\end_layout

