\begin_layout Standard
The benchmark suite was intentionally selected to cover a broad spectrum of optimization challenges.
 Unimodal functions mainly evaluate convergence speed and exploitation capability,
 whereas multimodal functions assess the ability of the optimizer to avoid premature convergence and escape local optima.
 Ill-conditioned functions examine numerical robustness under narrow search valleys,
 while composite and weak global structure functions evaluate the balance between exploration and exploitation.
 Finally,
 non-separable problems assess the capability of the algorithm to optimize strongly interacting decision variables,
 which are frequently encountered in real-world optimization problems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Experimental Protocol and Performance Measures
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A series of experiments were carried out for the previously mentioned functions and these experiments were executed on an AMD RYZEN 5950X with 128GB RAM.
 The operating system of the running machine was Debian Linux.
 Each experiment was conducted 30 times,
 with different random numbers each time and the averages were recorded.
 The software used in the experiments was coded in  C++ using the freely available optimization environment of OPTIMUS 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "OPTIMUS"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 which can be downloaded from
\series bold
 
\series default

\begin_inset Flex URL
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
https://github.com/itsoulos/OPTIMUS
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (accessed on 23 June 2026).
 The adoption of the publicly available OPTIMUS optimization framework improves the reproducibility of the experimental study and facilitates independent verification of the reported results by other researchers.
 All comparative methods were independently implemented and evaluated within the same experimental framework and were not directly adopted from the corresponding literature.
 All algorithms were implemented in C++ and executed under identical hardware and software conditions to ensure a fair and consistent comparison.
 Specifically,
 the number of agents (population size) was set to 200 for all algorithms,
 the maximum number of iterations was fixed at 200 and the local search rate was uniformly set to 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{l}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $=0.05$
\end_inset

 (local search probability).
 These shared settings ensure that performance differences arise from algorithmic design rather than differences in experimental configuration.
 Algorithm specific parameters were selected according to standard practices reported in the literature and were kept constant throughout all experiments.
 No problem specific parameter tuning was applied in order to avoid bias and to maintain methodological consistency.
 The parameter values were selected according to preliminary experiments and recommendations reported for the original EAO algorithm.
 To ensure fair comparisons,
 identical parameter values were maintained for all benchmark problems and competing algorithms whenever applicable.
 Although the influence of individual parameters was not investigated separately for every benchmark problem,
 the proposed algorithm exhibited stable performance under the selected configuration.
 A comprehensive parameter sensitivity analysis is considered an interesting direction for future work.
