\begin_layout Standard
Figure
\series bold
 
\series default

\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:The-proposed-method"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 presents a comparative analysis of the examined optimization algorithms in terms of the number of objective function evaluations required to achieve convergence.
 The comparison includes GENETIC (GA),
 DE,
 GWO,
 PARALLELDE,
 SAOP,
 BGWO,
 WOA and the PROPOSED method.
 Since the number of function evaluations represents a direct measure of computational effort,
 lower values indicate higher optimization efficiency.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As illustrated in the figure the PROPOSED algorithm exhibits one of the lowest median numbers of function evaluations while also maintaining the smallest variability among the examined methods.
 The narrow distribution of results indicates a high degree of robustness and consistent convergence behavior across the benchmark problems.
 In contrast,
 the GENETIC,
 WOA,
 BGWO and PARALLELDE algorithms display substantially larger dispersion and generally higher evaluation counts suggesting increased computational requirements and less stable convergence performance.
 The DE GWO and SAOP algorithms also achieve relatively low numbers of function evaluations however,
 they exhibit either greater variability or less consistent behavior compared with the proposed method.
 To assess whether the observed differences are statistically significant a Kruskal–Wallis non-parametric test was performed.
 The obtained result (p < 0.0001) indicates that statistically significant differences exist among the compared algorithms.
 Consequently,
 the null hypothesis that all algorithms exhibit identical performance distributions can be rejected with a high level of confidence.
 The reduced spread of the proposed method combined with its consistently low number of function evaluations suggests that the algorithm is able to efficiently balance exploration and exploitation throughout the optimization process.
 This behavior can be attributed to the cooperative subpopulation structure the information dissemination mechanism and the parallel search strategy incorporated into the proposed framework which collectively facilitate the rapid discovery and propagation of high-quality solutions.
 Overall,
 the results demonstrate that the proposed approach combines low computational cost with highly stable convergence behavior.
 The combination of efficiency robustness and consistency across a diverse set of benchmark functions highlights the effectiveness of the proposed method for solving complex optimization problems particularly in high-dimensional search spaces.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
High-Dimensional Benchmark Problems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To further investigate the scalability of the proposed optimization framework,
 additional experiments were conducted in high dimensions and more specifically for dimensions 50,
 100,
 200,
 300,
 400,
 500.
 The results demonstrate that the performance of the examined algorithms is strongly affected by both problem dimensionality and the characteristics of the objective-function landscape.
 On the Rotated Rosenbrock function,
 the proposed method remains competitive across most dimensional settings,
 although no single algorithm consistently achieves the lowest number of function evaluations.
 In dimensions 50,
 100,
 and 200,
 the proposed method requires 9549,
 14,607,
 and 17,312 function evaluations,
 respectively,
 outperforming several established approaches,
 including GA,
 DE,
 WOA,
 BICCA 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "BICCA"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 SHADE-ILS 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "SHADE_ILS"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and MLSHADE-SPA 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "MLSHADESPA"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 However,
 ParallelDE and,
 in some cases,
 SAOP,
 GWO or BGWO achieve lower computational requirements,
 indicating that the relative performance depends on the specific dimensional setting.
 At 300 and 400 dimensions,
 the performance of the proposed method deteriorates,
 particularly for the 400-dimensional Rotated Rosenbrock instance.
 Nevertheless,
 a considerable improvement is observed at 500 dimensions,
 where the proposed method requires 25,823 function evaluations.
 This value is substantially lower than those obtained by GA,
 DE,
 GWO,
 SAOP,
 BGWO,
 WOA,
 BICCA,
 MLSHADE-SPA and SHADE-ILS,
 while only ParallelDE achieves a better result.
 This finding indicates that the proposed cooperative framework can retain competitive performance even in extremely high-dimensional search spaces,
 although its behavior is not strictly monotonic as dimensionality increases.
 A favorable behavior is also observed for the Weierstrass function.
 For the 50-dimensional instance,
 the proposed method requires fewer evaluations than BICCA,
 SHADE-ILS,
 and MLSHADE-SPA,
 although WOA obtains the best result.
 At dimensions 100 and 200,
 the proposed method achieves the lowest number of function evaluations among the methods reported in tables 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:table8"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:table9"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

.
 In particular,
 it requires 7820 and 6018 evaluations respectively demonstrating that the proposed search mechanisms can effectively address highly multimodal landscapes as dimensionality increases.
 Overall,
 the results suggest that the proposed method provides a competitive balance between computational cost and scalability.
 Its advantage is more evident in several high-dimensional and multimodal instances,
 whereas alternative methods may perform better on particular problem configurations.
 Therefore,
 the experimental findings support the robustness of the proposed framework,
 without indicating universal superiority over all competing algorithms.
\end_layout

