\begin_layout Standard
As shown in table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:tab8-2-2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 the adaptive formulation achieved a lower number of objective function evaluations than the constant setting 
\begin_inset Formula $A=1$
\end_inset

 in all examined dimensions.
 Averaged across the eleven test instances,
 the adaptive configuration required approximately 5405 evaluations,
 compared with approximately 5750 evaluations for the constant configuration,
 corresponding to an average reduction of about 5.5%.
 The most pronounced improvement was observed at 150 dimensions,
 where the adaptive formulation required 4715 evaluations,
 whereas the constant setting required 6513 evaluations,
 representing a reduction of approximately 27.6%.
 These results indicate that dynamically adjusting the contribution of the best-solution attraction term is more computationally efficient than applying its maximum value throughout the entire optimization process.
 The adaptive schedule prevents the attraction component from remaining excessively strong during all iterations while progressively incorporating guidance from the current best solution.
 Consequently,
 the experimental results validate the design rationale of the proposed adaptive factor,
 demonstrating that gradually increasing the attraction toward the current best solution provides a more effective balance between exploration and exploitation than using a constant maximum attraction throughout the optimization process.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Wall-Clock Execution Time Analysis
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:tab8-2-2-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 presents the wall-clock execution time of the proposed PEAO framework for different numbers of clusters.
 The results indicate that configurations with a moderate number of clusters,
 particularly 10 and 20,
 provide the most favorable computational performance.
 This behavior suggests that these configurations achieve a better balance between parallel workload distribution,
 communication cost and convergence efficiency.
 For the Attractive Sector function,
 execution time increases gradually with dimensionality for all configurations.
 The use of 10 clusters consistently produces the lowest execution time across all examined dimensions,
 ranging from 5.321 seconds at D=100 to 13.033 seconds at D=500.
 The configuration with 20 clusters follows closely,
 whereas the use of 30 clusters results in the highest execution time in every case.
 This indicates that increasing the number of clusters beyond a moderate level introduces additional coordination and communication overhead without providing a corresponding computational benefit.
 The influence of the number of clusters is considerably more pronounced for the Rosenbrock function.
 The configurations with 5 and 30 clusters exhibit a substantial increase in execution time as dimensionality grows.
 At D=500,
 they require 197.680 and 203.496 seconds,
 respectively.
 In contrast,
 the configurations with 10 and 20 clusters require only 13.571 and 13.395 seconds.
 Therefore,
 the moderate-cluster configurations reduce the execution time by more than one order of magnitude in the highest-dimensional Rosenbrock instances.
 The configuration with 10 clusters achieves the lowest execution time at dimensions 100 and 300,
 while the configuration with 20 clusters performs slightly better at dimensions 200,
 400 and 500.
 However,
 the differences between these two configurations are generally small compared with their substantial advantage over the 5 and 30-cluster configurations.
 Overall,
 the results demonstrate that increasing the number of clusters does not necessarily lead to improved computational performance.
 A very small number of clusters may limit the benefits of workload decomposition,
 whereas an excessive number may increase synchronization and communication overhead.
 Consequently,
 configurations with 10 or 20 clusters appear to offer the most effective trade-off between parallelism and computational cost,
 with 10 clusters providing the most consistently favorable performance across both benchmark functions.
\end_layout

