\begin_layout Subsection
Effect of Communication Strategies on Function Evaluations and Execution Time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To further investigate the influence of the communication strategies.
 Figures 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Comparison-of-objective"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Comparison-of-execution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Comparison-of-objective-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Comparison-of-execution-1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"
nolink "false"

\end_inset

 present the average number of objective function evaluations and execution time obtained by the three communication strategies for the Attractive Sector and Rosenbrock benchmark functions over problem dimensions ranging from 100 to 500.
 The results indicate that the three strategies exhibit similar scalability as the problem dimension increases.
 Nevertheless,
 Strategy 2 consistently requires the lowest number of objective function evaluations in most problem instances,
 while also achieving the lowest or nearly lowest execution time.
 Although the observed differences are relatively small,
 these findings suggest that Strategy 2 provides a slightly more efficient balance between information exchange and computational overhead,
 making it the preferred communication strategy for the proposed PEAO framework.
\end_layout

