\begin_layout Subsection
Real-World Optimization Problems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To further examine the practical efficiency and scalability of the proposed optimization algorithm,
 two real-world optimization problems were investigated:
 the GasCycle 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "GasCycle"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 engineering design problem and the LennardJones13 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Lennard,Lennard-1"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 molecular optimization problem.
 These problems were selected because they differ substantially in their mathematical formulation and optimization characteristics,
 thereby providing complementary test cases for evaluating the algorithm under realistic conditions.
 To complement the benchmark-function analysis,
 both problems were evaluated in their original fixed-dimensional formulations.
 GasCycle consists of four decision variables,
 whereas LennardJones13 comprises 39 decision variables corresponding to the three-dimensional coordinates of 13 atoms.
 Consequently,
 these experiments assess the practical performance of the evaluated methods on representative real-world optimization problems and should not be interpreted as a dimensional scalability analysis.
 Each problem was solved in 30 independent runs using the experimental protocol and convergence-based stopping criterion described in Section 3.2.
 Performance was evaluated in terms of the mean and standard deviation of the final objective-function value,
 the average number of objective function evaluations required until termination and the average wall-clock execution time.
 Success rates were reported only when a reliable reference optimum and the predefined success tolerance were available.
 The two problems represent complementary optimization scenarios.
 GasCycle is a low-dimensional engineering design problem involving thermal-cycle parameters and feasibility constraints,
 whereas LennardJones13 is a highly non-convex molecular energy minimization problem characterized by numerous local minima.
 Owing to their different objective-function scales and problem dimensionalities,
 the results are analyzed separately rather than combined into a single overall performance measure.
 The corresponding experimental results are summarized in Tables 
