\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Discussion"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Effect of the Cooperative Cluster Structure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The experimental results indicate that the behavior of PEAO is strongly influenced by the number of cooperating subpopulations.
 Under the examined benchmark functions and parameter settings,
 configurations with 10 and 20 subpopulations generally required fewer objective function evaluations and exhibited lower variability than configurations with 5 or 30 subpopulations.
 This finding suggests that a moderate population decomposition can provide a favorable balance between distributed exploration and the availability of sufficient individuals for local refinement.
 Nevertheless,
 the results should not be interpreted as demonstrating that 10 or 20 subpopulations are universally optimal.
 The most appropriate configuration may depend on the population size,
 problem landscape,
 dimensionality,
 computing platform and communication frequency.
 The present findings are therefore restricted to the experimental conditions examined in this study.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Impact of the Propagation Mechanism
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The comparison between the configurations with and without propagation showed a substantial reduction in objective function evaluations when propagation was enabled.
 The paired Wilcoxon signed-rank test confirmed that the observed difference was statistically significant (p < 0.0001).
 These results indicate that,
 under the examined settings,
 the transfer of promising solutions among subpopulations reduces redundant search and accelerates convergence.
 However,
 objective function evaluations do not directly measure communication and synchronization overhead.
 Therefore,
 the propagation experiment primarily demonstrates an improvement in evaluation efficiency and should not by itself be interpreted as proof of reduced total execution cost.
 The separate wall-clock analysis complements this metric.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Analysis of Communication Strategies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The experiments involving the 1-to-1,
 1-to-N,
 N-to-1,
 and N-to-N topologies demonstrate that the information-exchange pattern materially affects the behavior of PEAO.
 Among the configurations examined using 10 subpopulations,
 N-to-N generally achieved the lowest objective function evaluation count and the smallest variability.
 The Friedman test indicated statistically significant differences among the evaluated topologies.
 These results suggest that broad information dissemination can accelerate the diffusion of promising solutions and reduce redundant exploration.
 Nevertheless,
 extensive communication may also increase synchronization overhead or reduce population diversity in other settings.
 Therefore,
 the observed advantage of N-to-N is restricted to the benchmark functions,
 communication frequency,
 population size and number of subpopulations examined in the present study.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Performance on Practical Optimization Problems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The experiments on GasCycle and LennardJones13 provide an additional assessment of the evaluated methods on two practical optimization problems with different mathematical characteristics.
 GasCycle is a four-variable constrained thermal-cycle problem,
 whereas LennardJones13 is a 39-variable non-convex molecular-energy problem.
 The results are interpreted in terms of final solution quality,
 objective function evaluations,
 and wall-clock execution time.
 Because each problem was evaluated only in its original fixed-dimensional formulation,
 these experiments do not provide evidence of dimensional scalability.
 Instead,
 they examine whether the competitive behavior observed on the benchmark functions is also maintained on two practical problem formulations.
 The conclusions are therefore limited to the specific instances and experimental settings considered.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Comparative Performance Evaluation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The comparison with the selected metaheuristic algorithms indicates that PEAO achieved competitive performance across the examined benchmark set.
 It obtained one of the lower overall objective function evaluation counts and displayed comparatively limited variability on several functions.
 Nevertheless,
 individual competing methods achieved better performance on particular functions and dimensional configurations.
 The Kruskal–Wallis test indicated that statistically significant differences exist among the performance distributions of the compared algorithms.
 This result establishes that the algorithms do not exhibit identical behavior,
 but it does not by itself prove that PEAO is superior to every competing method.
 Consequently,
 the comparative findings should be interpreted jointly with the function-by-function results,
 final objective values,
 success rates and wall-clock execution times.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Overall Assessment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Overall,
 the results indicate that PEAO achieved competitive performance under the benchmark functions,
 dimensions,
 parameter settings,
 stopping conditions and computing platform examined in this study.
 The ablation experiments show that population decomposition,
 propagation,
 information-exchange topology and adaptive search control materially affect the behavior of the method.
 However,
 several competing algorithms achieved better performance on individual functions or dimensional configurations.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusions
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Conclusions"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This study introduced the Parallel Enzyme Action Optimizer (PEAO),
 a cooperative population-based optimization framework that extends the original EAO through parallel subpopulation evolution,
 controlled propagation,
 alternative information-exchange topologies,
 adaptive search control,
 optional local refinement and convergence-based termination.
 The proposed structure was designed to maintain population diversity,
 disseminate promising search information and balance global exploration with local refinement.
 The ablation experiments demonstrated that the number of subpopulations,
 activation of the propagation mechanism,
 information-exchange topology and adaptive factor materially influence the behavior of the algorithm.
 Under the examined experimental settings,
 moderate subpopulation configurations generally provided a favorable balance between computational effort and search diversity,
 while propagation substantially reduced the number of objective function evaluations.
 Among the examined topologies,
 N-to-N generally achieved the lowest evaluation counts when 10 subpopulations were employed.
 The comparative experiments indicate that PEAO achieved competitive performance on the considered benchmark functions and high-dimensional instances of up to 500 decision variables.
 The method obtained comparatively low objective function evaluation counts and consistent final-solution quality on several problems.
 However,
 competing algorithms achieved better results on individual functions and dimensional configurations.
 Therefore,
 the findings do not establish universal superiority of PEAO and are restricted to the benchmark suite,
 parameter settings,
 stopping conditions,
 implementations and computing platform examined in this study.
 The experiments on GasCycle and LennardJones13 provide an additional assessment of the method on two fixed-dimensional practical optimization problems.
 These experiments examine practical applicability but should not be interpreted as evidence of dimensional scalability.
 Future work will investigate self-adaptive communication and propagation policies,
 dynamic management of subpopulations,
 derivative-free alternatives to the optional local-refinement stage and formal parallel scalability experiments using fixed algorithmic configurations and different numbers of processing threads.
 Further evaluation on standardized large-scale,
 constrained,
 dynamic and multi-objective optimization problems would also provide a broader assessment of the applicability of the proposed framework.
\end_layout

